  "sections": [
    {
      "id": "SEC1",
      "type": "heading",
      "title": "Introduction to SAP Modules"
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC2",
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "SAP S/4HANA consists of multiple functional modules, each responsible for managing a specific business process. These modules work together using a centralized database, enabling seamless information flow across the organization."
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC3",
      "type": "callout",
      "calloutType": "important",
      "title": "Key Concept",
      "content": "SAP modules are integrated-not isolated. A business transaction in one module automatically impacts related modules."
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC4",
      "type": "heading",
      "title": "Major SAP Functional Modules"
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC5",
      "type": "table",
      "title": "SAP Modules Overview",
      "headers": [
        "Module",
        "Full Form",
        "Purpose"
      ],
      "rows": [
        ["FI", "Financial Accounting", "Financial transactions and reporting"],
        ["CO", "Controlling", "Cost planning and profitability analysis"],
        ["MM", "Materials Management", "Procurement and inventory management"],
        ["SD", "Sales and Distribution", "Sales order and billing"],
        ["PP", "Production Planning", "Manufacturing planning"],
        ["QM", "Quality Management", "Quality inspections"],
        ["PM", "Plant Maintenance", "Equipment maintenance"],
        ["EWM", "Extended Warehouse Management", "Warehouse operations"],
        ["TM", "Transportation Management", "Transportation planning and execution"],
        ["HCM", "Human Capital Management", "Employee management"]
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC6",
      "type": "heading",
      "title": "How SAP Modules Work Together"
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC7",
      "type": "process-flow",
      "title": "Integrated Business Process",
      "orientation": "horizontal",
      "steps": [
        "Sales (SD)",
        "Procurement (MM)",
        "Production (PP)",
        "Warehouse (EWM)",
        "Transportation (TM)",
        "Finance (FI)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC8",
      "type": "heading",
      "title": "SAP Transportation Management (TM)"
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC9",
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "SAP TM manages transportation planning, carrier selection, freight execution, monitoring and freight settlement. It integrates closely with Sales, Procurement, Warehouse Management and Finance."
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC10",
      "type": "table",
      "title": "SAP TM Integration",
      "headers": [
        "Module",
        "Integration"
      ],
      "rows": [
        ["SD", "Sales Orders and Deliveries"],
        ["MM", "Purchase Orders and Inbound Deliveries"],
        ["EWM", "Warehouse Execution"],
        ["FI", "Freight Settlement"],
        ["GTS", "Compliance"],
        ["BTP", "Extensions and Integrations"]
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC11",
      "type": "heading",
      "title": "Business Example"
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC12",
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "A customer places an order through SD. Materials are procured using MM, manufactured through PP, stored in EWM, transported using TM and finally invoiced through FI. Every module contributes to the complete business process."
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC13",
      "type": "comparison",
      "title": "MM vs SD vs TM",
      "leftTitle": "Module",
      "rightTitle": "Primary Responsibility",
      "rows": [
        {
          "feature": "MM",
          "left": "Procurement",
          "right": "Purchase & Inventory"
        },
        {
          "feature": "SD",
          "left": "Sales",
          "right": "Order & Delivery"
        },
        {
          "feature": "TM",
          "left": "Transportation",
          "right": "Planning & Freight Execution"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC14",
      "type": "heading",
      "title": "Benefits of Integrated Modules"
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC15",
      "type": "bullet-list",
      "items": [
        "Single source of truth",
        "No duplicate data",
        "Real-time communication",
        "Automated business processes",
        "Improved decision making",
        "Lower operational costs",
        "End-to-end process visibility"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC16",
      "type": "callout",
      "calloutType": "example",
      "title": "Real Project Example",
      "content": "In an automotive company, SAP TM automatically receives outbound deliveries from SAP SD, plans shipments, assigns carriers and sends freight costs to SAP FI for settlement."
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC17",
      "type": "callout",
      "calloutType": "interview-tip",
      "title": "Interview Tip",
      "content": "When explaining SAP TM, always mention its integration with SD, MM, EWM and FI. Integration questions are very common in interviews."
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC18",
      "type": "callout",
      "calloutType": "warning",
      "title": "Common Mistake",
      "content": "Do not describe SAP modules as independent systems. They are tightly integrated and share master and transactional data."
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC19",
      "type": "heading",
      "title": "Revision Summary"
    },
    {
      "id": "SEC20",
      "type": "bullet-list",
      "items": [
        "SAP consists of multiple integrated modules.",
        "Each module supports a business function.",
        "SAP TM integrates with SD, MM, EWM and FI.",
        "Business processes span multiple modules.",
        "Integration is one of SAP's biggest strengths."
      ]
    }
  ],
